Dataset & Goals

Goals

The objective of this project is to be able to make predictions on what a players best position is on the field based on their attributes in the Fifa dataset. Each player will have a set of skills and defining characteristics. Based on these inputs I will create an ML model that can decide where they should play.
I beleive a tool like this could be useful to management staff when assessing new players. They will have the data related to their skill set and features like height, age etc and from this can decide where they should play. This can be especially useful when looking for now talent,discussing with a player who wants to be a stiker but your data would suggest otherwise and you play them in a more appropriate position or if dealing with an ageing player who usually goes in midfield but as their speed and fitness decreases the model might show they are better suited to a defending role.


Data Source

The data set used was taken from kagle, a great source for data science entusiasts to explore new data, enhance their skills and have some fun. The Fifa 22 Plater data set can be found here. The datasets provided include the players data for the Career Mode from FIFA 15 to FIFA 22 ("players_22.csv"). This is really cool because you can concaternate the data set from the past 7 years, monitor player progression or young prospects who never quite made it and evaluate the "potential" Fifa applied to them at various years. For the sake of this experiment I am focusing on the 2022 Player Data Set and the goal is to be able to create a K-Nearest Neighbor model that can accurately predict the players position. This project was done using Python, so lets take a look at the dataset using Pandas.

Data Cleansing

Data cleansing can be an iterative process and can depend on the end goal of the project. We may come back to data cleansing later if we find that our data is still not suitable for the algorithim. From first glance I think the initial steps we can take are:

  1. Removing columns that will not help in grouping players into their positions
  2. Check the columns we are left with for null values and replace with better data
  3. Check remaining columns for outliers and see if they make sense

Column Inspection

</br> It is necessary to drop a lot of the columns becasue useless information will slow down training and could corupt the model or distort the results.

From that simple analysis I think the best corse of action is:

  1. Drop values with null value_eur because it is less than .4%. Normally not acceptable but its such a small amount.
  2. Null goalkeeping_speed is probably every non-gaolkeeper in the dataset, which is a lot. Since they are not goalkeepers I will give them a value worse than the lowest speed in the dataset
  3. The remaining values it would make sence to give them the median value

#Drop null values for value_eur
data=data.dropna(subset=['value_eur'])

gkSpeeds=gkSpeeds.describe()
print(gkSpeeds)
#Give non-keepers a speed that is 3 standard deviations less than the mean. Also lower than slowest actual keepers value

medianCols=list(nulls.index)
medianCols.remove('goalkeeping_speed')
medianCols.remove('value_eur')
data=data.fillna(value=data[medianCols].median())

Outliers Approach¶

I'm going to take a fairly easy approach here from eyeballing the above graph.
The first column highlights a column that is highly skewed. This probably represents a bigger problem in football altogehter where the majority of players are paid a similar amount but then start players or specific teams in top leagues where players are getting paid vastly more. These players should not be ignored from our data but because of how skewed the data is I'm going to drop this column.
Then the same could be said for all goalkeeping stats. Most palyers are not goalkeeprs so the majority of the values are low, and all actual goalkeepers are going to look like outliers. Since this is actually a perfect way of identifying gaolkeepers these columns and all rows will be kept.
From the greaph the majority of the rest of the data is relatively centered or within the whiskers of the box plot and as I don't want to ditch highly skilled or terrible players I'm going to keep all of these values.

Training

Now lets run the KNN algorithm!¶

K-Nearest Neighbors is a machine learning technique and algorithm that can be used for both regression and classification tasks. K-Nearest Neighbors examines the labels of a chosen number of data points surrounding a target data point, in order to make a prediction about the class that the data point falls into.
I also considered using the K-Means algo becasue I think it could do a good job of classifying the data since we know the number of groups but for the sake of doing hyperparameter tuning with a test-accuracy I needed a supervised technique.

In [81]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

import sagemaker
from sagemaker import get_execution_role
from sagemaker.serializers import CSVSerializer
from sagemaker.deserializers import JSONDeserializer
from sagemaker.amazon.amazon_estimator import get_image_uri

######
# Name : trained_estimator_from_hyperparams
######
# Def  : Train a KNN model 
######
# Args : - s3_train_data - Path to S3 training data
# Args : - hyperparams - Params for the KNN model
# Args : - output_path - S3 path where model will be saved 
# Args : - s3_test_data - Optional Path to S3 training data
######
# Name : trained_estimator_from_hyperparams
def train_knn_from_hyperparams(s3_train_data, hyperparams, output_path, s3_test_data=None):
    """
    Create an Estimator from the given hyperparams, fit to training data,
    and return a deployed predictor

    """
    # set up the estimator
    knn = sagemaker.estimator.Estimator(
        get_image_uri(boto3.Session().region_name, "knn"),
        get_execution_role(),
        instance_count=1,
        instance_type="ml.m5.2xlarge",
        output_path=output_path,
        sagemaker_session=sagemaker.Session(),
    )
    knn.set_hyperparameters(**hyperparams)

    # train a model. fit_input contains the locations of the train and test data
    fit_input = {"train": s3_train_data}
    if s3_test_data is not None:
        fit_input["test"] = s3_test_data
    knn.fit(fit_input)
    return knn

In [83]:
import time

######
# Name : fifa_knn_predictor
######
# Def  : Make a prediction of a players position using KNN 
######
# Args : - knn_estimator - Sagemaker trained knn model
# Args : - estimator_name - Name we give to our estimator 
# Args : - instance_type - Hardware Sagemaker will use for predictions
# Args : - endpoint_name - Sagemaker endoint name for logging
######
# Name : trained_estimator_from_hyperparams
def fifa_knn_predictor(knn_estimator, estimator_name, instance_type, endpoint_name=None):
    knn_predictor = knn_estimator.deploy(
        initial_instance_count=1, instance_type=instance_type, endpoint_name=endpoint_name
    )
    knn_predictor.serializer = CSVSerializer()
    knn_predictor.deserializer = JSONDeserializer()
    return knn_predictor

instance_type = "ml.c4.large"
model_name = "knn_%s" % instance_type
endpoint_name = "knn-ml-c4-large-%s" % (str(time.time()).replace(".", "-"))
print("setting up the endpoint..")
predictor = fifa_knn_predictor(
    knn_estimator, model_name, instance_type, endpoint_name=endpoint_name
)

Now lets test it out!¶

We now have an active endpoint hosted on dedicated hardware to make inference.
To test out this model I'm going to use the starting 11 from my favourite team, Liverpool!

In [84]:
batches = np.array_split(X_test, 100)
print(f"data split into 100 batches, of size {batches[0].shape[0]}.")

# obtain an np array with the predictions for the entire test set
start_time = time.time()
predictions = []
for batch in batches:
    result = predictor.predict(batch, initial_args={"ContentType": "text/csv"})
    cur_predictions = np.array(
        [result["predictions"][i]["predicted_label"] for i in range(len(result["predictions"]))]
    )
    predictions.append(cur_predictions)
predictions = np.concatenate(predictions)
run_time = time.time() - start_time

test_size = y_test.shape[0]
num_correct = sum(predictions == y_test)
accuracy = num_correct / float(test_size)
print("time required for predicting %d data point: %.2f seconds" % (test_size, run_time))
print("accuracy of model: %.1f%%" % (accuracy * 100))

import colorama
from colorama import Fore as colour
def printRed(text):
    print(colour.RED+text)
    
def printGreen(text):
    print(colour.GREEN+text)

revPosDict={0.0:'Goal Keeper',1.0:'Defender',2.0:"Midfielder",3.0:"Forward"}
#Get the Liverpool starting 11
liverpool=fifa.loc[fifa['club_name']=='Liverpool'][:11]

for i in liverpool.index:
    realPos=revPosDict[normData['position'].loc[i]]
    predPos=predictor.predict(np.array(normData2.drop(columns=['position']).loc[i]).astype(float))
    predPos=revPosDict[predPos['predictions'][0]['predicted_label']]
    name=liverpool['short_name'].loc[i]
    if realPos==predPos:
        printGreen("Player {name} is a {pos} and we predicted {pred}".format(name=name,pos=realPos,pred=predPos))
    if realPos!=predPos:
        printRed("Player {name} is a {pos} and we predicted {pred}".format(name=name,pos=realPos,pred=predPos))

def delete_endpoint(predictor):
    try:
        boto3.client("sagemaker").delete_endpoint(EndpointName=predictor.endpoint_name)
        print(f"Deleted {predictor.endpoint_name}")
    except:
        print(f"Already deleted: {predictor.endpoint_name}")


delete_endpoint(predictor)

Conclusion¶

  • We imported some csv data on Fifa_22 players.
  • Cleaned and normalized and removed outliers from the date to be used for ML.
  • Converted the CSV data to Record-IO Protobuf and stored it in S3.
  • Used the S3 datasets to traing a model on specified hardware to get a quick training time.
  • We created a KNN model with an accuracy of 82.2%
  • We then created a Sagemaker endpoint using cheaper hardware for inference to make predictions.

Hyperparameter tuning

Set Up</h2>

In [90]:
from sagemaker.tuner import (
    IntegerParameter,
    CategoricalParameter,
    ContinuousParameter,
    HyperparameterTuner,
)

# set up the estimator
output_path='s3://sagemaker-us-east-1-022761975017/knn-cwright-example-2022-04-06/auto-tune/output'
knn = sagemaker.estimator.Estimator(
    get_image_uri(boto3.Session().region_name, "knn"),
    get_execution_role(),
    instance_count=1,
    instance_type="ml.m5.2xlarge",
    output_path=output_path,
    sagemaker_session=sagemaker.Session(),
)

#Choose hyperparams
#Fixed
hyperparams = {"feature_dim": 45, "predictor_type": "classifier"}
knn.set_hyperparameters(**hyperparams)
#Tune-able
hyperparameter_ranges = {
    "k": IntegerParameter(5, 20),
    "sample_size": IntegerParameter(2000,20000, scaling_type='Logarithmic') #make sue to use logarithmic scale for large vals
}

#Objective we will measure on
objective_metric_name = "test:accuracy"
objective_metric_func = "Maximize"
#Max jobs to run
max_jobs=1 #Running the tuning with just a single job first to make sure we don't get any errors
#Max parallel jobs to run - note tuning uses previous results so don't do too much in parallel.
max_parallel_jobs=2
tuner = HyperparameterTuner(
    knn,
    objective_metric_name,
    hyperparameter_ranges,
    objective_type=objective_metric_func,
    max_jobs=max_jobs,
    max_parallel_jobs=max_parallel_jobs,
)

The method get_image_uri has been renamed in sagemaker>=2.
See: https://sagemaker.readthedocs.io/en/stable/v2.html for details.

#Get new predictions
batches = np.array_split(X_test, 100)
print(f"data split into 100 batches, of size {batches[0].shape[0]}.")

# obtain an np array with the predictions for the entire test set
start_time = time.time()
predictions = []
predictor.serializer = CSVSerializer()
predictor.deserializer = JSONDeserializer()

for batch in batches:
    result = predictor.predict(batch, initial_args={"ContentType": "text/csv"})
    cur_predictions = np.array(
        [result["predictions"][i]["predicted_label"] for i in range(len(result["predictions"]))]
    )
    predictions.append(cur_predictions)
predictions = np.concatenate(predictions)
run_time = time.time() - start_time

test_size = y_test.shape[0]
num_correct = sum(predictions == y_test)
accuracy = num_correct / float(test_size)
print("time required for predicting %d data point: %.2f seconds" % (test_size, run_time))
print("accuracy of model: %.1f%%" % (accuracy * 100))

Lets try and plot some of these values in an effort to show the groupings that the model is creating. To this though we will need to decrease the feature space from 45 to a human readible number. Because visually it is difficult to represent all features I will perform PCA on the original data to find the components the make the biggest impact when choosing a players positions. These components are not necessarily features themselves but some vector representation of possibly multiple features.

def delete_endpoint(predictor):
    try:
        boto3.client("sagemaker").delete_endpoint(EndpointName=predictor.endpoint_name)
        print(f"Deleted {predictor.endpoint_name}")
    except:
        print(f"Already deleted: {predictor.endpoint_name}")


delete_endpoint(predictor)
